a, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Lindsey","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Lindsay  .","Irish: shortened and Anglicized form of various Gaelic surnames, as for example <b>Ó Loingsigh</b> (see   Lynch   1), <b>Mac Giolla Fhionntóg</b> (see   McClintock  ), and <b>Ó Fhloinn</b> (see   Flynn   and   Lynn  )."],"variants":[{"name":"McClintock","meanings":["Scottish and northern Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Gille Fhionndaig</b> ‘son of the servant of (Saint) <i>Fionntóg</i>’, a personal name derived from a pet form of <i>fionn</i> ‘white’. Compare   Lindsey  .","History: A Scottish family of this name settled in Donegal in the late 16th century."]},{"name":"Lindsay","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name from Lindsey in Lincolnshire, England. This is first found in the form <i>Lindissi</i>, apparently a derivative of the British name of   Lincoln  . To this was later added the Old English element <i>ēg</i> ‘island’, since the place was virtually cut off by the surrounding fenland. The surname was taken to Scotland at an early date and is the name of an important and powerful Scottish family.","Irish: adopted as an equivalent ofvarious Gaelic names (see   Lindsey  )."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"William de Lindsey was born in 1215, in Kilmarnock, Ayrshire, Scotland, United Kingdom. He had at least 1 daughter with Margaret Lindsey."},"et":{"1215–":"1215–Surnud","1220–Female":"1220–Surnud","1237–1304":"1237–1304","1215–Male":"1215–Surnud","1304":"1304","1215":"1215","1237":"1237","1220":"1220","of Kilmarnock, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Kilmarnock, Ayrshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Kilmarnock, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Kilmarnock, Ayrshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1215–":"1215–Kuollut","1220–Female":"1220–Kuollut","1237–1304":"1237–1304","1215–Male":"1215–Kuollut","1304":"1304","1215":"1215","1237":"1237","1220":"1220","of Kilmarnock, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Kilmarnock, Ayrshire, Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Kilmarnock, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Kilmarnock, Ayrshire, Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1215–":"1215–Décédé","1220–Female":"1220–Décédée","1237–1304":"1237–1304","1215–Male":"1215–Décédé","1304":"1304","1215":"1215","1237":"1237","1220":"1220","of Kilmarnock, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Kilmarnock, Ayrshire, Écosse, Royaume-Uni","Kilmarnock, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Kilmarnock, Ayrshire, Écosse, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"William de Lindsey est né en 1215, à Kilmarnock, Ayrshire, Écosse, Royaume-Uni. Il a eu au moins 1 fille avec Margaret Lindsey."},"de":{"1215–":"1215–Verstorben","1220–Female":"1220–Verstorben","1237–1304":"1237–1304","1215–Male":"1215–Verstorben","1304":"1304","1215":"1215","1237":"1237","122